30199	\N	1579	2044	ONAP APPC (Application Controller)	ONAP APPC is one of the components of the ONAP platform. It is responsible for handling the Life Cycle Management (LCM) of Virtual Network Functions (VNFs). ONAP APPC infrastructure is implemented on virtual machine in an OpenStack cloud in the Amsterdam release. ONAP APPC is created on the top of the OpenDaylight (ODL) platform. ONAP APPC contains three containers: VM#1: ONAP APPC(ODL Framework & APPC OSGI Bundles), VM#2: MYSQL DB, VM#3: DG Builder ( as of Amsterdam release) The ONAP APPC HTTP API supports LCM commands, allowing users to manage virtual applications and their components via other ONAP components.	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Application+Controller+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/appc	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	The project sites are all HTTPS:\r\nProject site: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Application+Controller+Project\r\nRepository: https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/appc https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/appc/cdt https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/appc/deployment	Met	The description of the software could be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=3246996	Met	The following URLs describe the process to join the community, developing the software and provide feedback: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Joining+the+Community,  https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Tracking+Issues+with+JIRA, https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developing+ONAP	Met	The process could be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies	Met	The Javascript code should meet the requirements except for the number of characters in a line of code specified by the styleguide\r\nhttps://google.github.io/styleguide/jsguide.html\r\nWe avoid the restriction on the number of characters in one line of code to improve readability. 30208	\N	1588	3192	ONAP VNFSDK	ONAP VNFSDK's mission is to simplify the process of developing and onboarding VNFs and expanding ONAP's VNF ecosystem. For Service Providers, VNFSDK will reduce the time and level of testing required to identify, select, and onboard a VNF.  For vendors, VNFSDK will reduce integration efforts by defining a standard for VNF packaging with widespread operator acceptance.  VNFSDK can be used in a validation/conformance testing program in the future.\r\n\r\nVNFSDK delivers automation tools for VNF product specification, packaging, publication and ingestion.\r\nThis project will also deliver a tool for: \r\n\r\n    package validation,\r\n    lifecycle test (framework)\r\n    functional test (framework)\r\n    Reference Repository for VNFs to enable CI/CD without dependency on service provider ingestion	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/VNF+SDK+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/vnfsdk	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/VNF+SDK+Project\r\nhttps://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/vnfsdk	Met	The description of the project can be found in http://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/vnfsdk/model.git/docs/release-notes.html	Met	The following URLs describe the process to join the community, developing the software and provide feekback: \r\nhttps://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Joining+the+Community \r\nhttps://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Tracking+Issues+with+JIRA \r\nhttps://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developing+ONAP	Met	The process could be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies\r\n	Met	The Javascript code should meet the requirements except for the number of characters in a line of code specified by the styleguide\r\nhttps://google.github.io/styleguide/jsguide.html\r\nWe avoid the restriction on the number of characters in one line of code to improve readability. 30211	\N	1591	2058	ONAP Active and Available Inventory	Active and Available Inventory (AAI) is the ONAP subsystem that provides real-time views of Resources and Services and their relationships. AAI not only forms a registry of active, available, and assigned assets, it also maintains up-to-date views of the multidimensional relationships among these assets, including their relevance to different components of ONAP. \r\n\r\nThis project targets a logically centralized reference point for service and resource details serving other ONAP components and non-ONAP systems to enable fulfillment, closed loop, reporting, and other operational use cases. Met	The Makefile runs go vet on each build and will fail the build with any vet failures.  "go lint" is also supported in the Makefile, and "go fmt" is also run on each build but that is only for syntax.\r\nhttps://github.com/rook/rook/blob/master/Makefile	Met	The Makefile runs go vet on each build and will fail the build with any vet failures. https://github.com/rook/rook/blob/master/Makefile	Met	It is a language feature that the go compiler does not have warning levels, so by default our "go build" is maximally strict.  From https://golang.org/doc/faq#unused_variables_and_imports: "Go compiler does not report warnings, only errors that prevent compilation. There are two reasons for having no warnings. First, if it's worth complaining about, it's worth fixing in the code. (And if it's not worth fixing, it's not worth mentioning.) Second, having the compiler generate warnings encourages the implementation to warn about weak cases that can make compilation noisy, masking real errors that should be fixed." 30222	\N	1604	2058	ONAP ESR (External System Register)	ONAP components need to talk with external systems such as VIM/VNFM/vendor SDNC/EMS to orchestrate a network service, for example, VF-C need to talk with VNFM to deploy a VNF. So they should get the information of available external systems from a registry before call the Interfaces of these external systems.  ESR provides a service to centralized management of the information (name, vendor, version, acess end point, etc.) of external systems. So the ONAP components can get the system information with unified API from a logical single point. 	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/External+System+Register	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/aai/esr-server	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	The project sites are all HTTPS: \r\nProject site: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/External+System+Register\r\nRepository: https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/aai/esr-server	Met	The description of the project can be found in:\r\nhttp://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aai/esr-gui.git/docs/platform/architecture.html	Met	The following URLs describe the process to join the community, developing the software and provide feekback: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Joining+the+Community https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Tracking+Issues+with+JIRA https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developing+ONAP	Met	The process could be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies	Met	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies describes requirements for acceptable contributions and is linked from the AAI project page. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Java+code+style shows java code style. https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developer+Best+Practices\r\nHere is the google java code style: https://google.github.io/styleguide/javaguide.html	Met	License can be found in: https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=aai/esr-server.git;a=blob;f=LICENSE.txt;h=67a5857a70de7d7f09d3777c7f99d7c0c7dc44b8;hb=HEAD	Met	The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI). 30226	\N	1608	2085	VF-C (Virtual Function Controller Project)	Virtual Function Controller Project  leverages ETSI NFV MANO architecture and information model as a reference, and implements full life cycle management and FCAPS of VNF and NS. It supports following functionality : \r\n\r\n NS and VNF lifecycle management based on the ONAP TOSCA and yang data model and workflow\r\n Integration with multi VNFMs via drivers, which include vendors VNFM and generic VNFM\r\n Integration with multi VNFs via generic VNFM, which does not provide VNFM function\r\n Integration with multi VIMS via Multi-VIM, which include the open source and commercial VIMs\r\n Micro service architecture and model driven resource orchestration and 30231	\N	1614	2096	ONAP POLICY	POLICY is the subsystem of ONAP that maintains, distributes, and operates on the set of rules that underlie ONAPs control, orchestration, and management functions.\r\n\r\nPOLICY provides a logically centralized environment for the creation and management of policies, including conditional rules. This provides the capability to create and validate policies/rules, identify overlaps, resolve conflicts, and derive additional policies as needed.\r\n\r\nPolicies are used to control, influence, and help ensure compliance with goals. Policies can support infrastructure, products and services, operation automation, and security. Users, including network and service designers, operations engineers, and security experts, can easily create, change, and manage policy rules from the POLICY Manager in the ONAP Portal.\r\n\r\nA policy is defined to create a condition, requirement, constraint, decision, or a need that must be provided, evaluated, maintained, and/or enforced. The policy is validated and corrected for any conflicts, and then placed in the appropriate repository, and made available for use by other subsystems and components. Alternately, some policies are directly distributed to policy decision engines such as Drools or XACML. In this manner, the constraints, decisions and actions to be taken are distributed.	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Policy+Framework+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/policy	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	The project sites are all HTTPS:\r\n\r\nProject site: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Policy+Framework+Project\r\n\r\nRepository: https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/policy	Met	The description of the project can be found at:\r\n\r\nhttp://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/policy/engine.git/docs/platform/index.html	Met	The following URLs describe the process to join the community, developing the software and provide feekback: \r\n\r\nhttps://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Joining+the+Community \r\n\r\nhttps://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Tracking+Issues+with+JIRA\r\n\r\nhttps://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Developing+ONAP\r\n	Met	The process could be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies	Met	The Javascript code should meet the requirements except for the number of characters in a line of code specified by the styleguide\r\nhttps://google.github.io/styleguide/jsguide.html\r\n\r\nWe avoid the restriction on the number of characters in one line of code to improve readability	Met	https://git.onap.org/policy/drools-pdp/tree/LICENSE.txt\r\n\r\nhttps://git.onap.org/policy/drools-applications/tree/LICENSE.txt\r\n\r\nhttps://git.onap.org/policy/engine/tree/LICENSE.txt\r\n\r\nhttps://git.onap.org/policy/common/tree/LICENSE.txt	Met	The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI). 30248	\N	1631	2117	ONAP Operations Manager	The Open Network Automation Platform (ONAP) Operations Manager (OOM) is responsible for life-cycle management of the ONAP platform itself; components such as MSO, SDNC, etc. It is not responsible for the management of services, VNFs or infrastructure instantiated by ONAP or used by ONAP to host such services or VNFs. OOM uses the open-source Kubernetes container management system as a means to manage the Docker containers that compose ONAP where the containers are hosted either directly on bare-metal servers or on VMs hosted by a 3rd party management system. OOM ensures that ONAP is easily deployable and maintainable throughout its life cycle while using hardware resources efficiently.	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/ONAP+Operations+Manager+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/oom	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. Using gerrit is documented here: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies and is linked from OOM project page. 30308	\N	1699	32	AppArmor	AppArmor is an effective and easy-to-use Linux application security system. AppArmor proactively protects the operating system and applications from external or internal threats, even zero-day attacks, by enforcing good behavior and preventing even unknown application flaws from being exploited. AppArmor security policies completely define what system resources individual applications can access, and with what privileges. 30312	\N	1703	2116	ONAP SDNC (SDN Controller)	The SDNC project provides a global network controller, built on the Common Controller Framework, which manages, assigns and provisions network resources.   As a "global" controller, the SDNC project is intended to run as one logical instance per enterprise, with potentially multiple geographically diverse virtual machines / docker containers in clusters to provide high availability.  The project also will support the ability to invoke other local SDN controllers, including third party SDN controllers.	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Software+Defined+Network+Controller+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/sdnc	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. 30326	\N	1718	2630	ONAP DCAE	Data Collection Analytics and Events (DCAE) is the data collection and analysis subsystem of ONAP. Its functions include among other things the collection of measurement and fault data from the network entities (Virtual Network Functions, Physical Network Functions, etc).  It provides also a framework for the normalization of data format, the transportation of data, analysis of data, and generations of ONAP events which can be received by other ONAP components such as Policy for subsequent operations like closed loops. 	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Data+Collection+Analytics+and+Events+Project	https://git.onap.org/dcaegen2	Apache-2.0 and Creative Commons licenses	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. 30341	\N	1737	2259	ONAP AAI UI 	The ONAP AAI UI is a service that interacts with ONAP AAI and provides users with a user interface to view and analyze AAI data. The main goal behind AAI UI is to provide a clear and user friendly view of ONAP AAI data.\r\n\r\nThe AAI UI is a small eco-system that is composed of a few micro-services.\r\nsparky-fe is the front end portion (and not captured in the current project)  \r\nsparky-be is the web server that serves the front-end\r\ndata-router is responsible for reading messages on a queue from AAI and keep the secondary database in sync\r\nsearch-data-service is an abstraction service that interacts with the secondary database\r\nrouter-core is a library containing the core camel components for the data router\r\n	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Active+and+Available+Inventory+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/aai/sparky-be	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. 30342	\N	1738	2272	vvp	The project is to develop a validation program to provide assurance of VNF interoperability with ONAP. Obtaining a validation shall be a self-service activity and should be against a reference release of ONAP for use by the VNF provider & any other validation authority.This project at ONAP will not operate as a Validation Authority and will create a process to identify and qualify Validation Authorities. Self-Certification may be considered as a Certification authority option. This project will provide a process to evolve the validation criteria based on experience and as the VN F Requirements & Guidelines evolve. At each release of ONAP, the scope of functionality tested and the test coverage for VNF validation may change. This Project will validate the VNF package integrity and provenance e.g. using signing & attestation. This Project will maintain the authoritative set of tests and test procedures for Validations of VNFs. This project shall develop the tests and test procedures traceable to the VNF Requirements & Guidelines.	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/VNF+Validation+Program+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/admin/projects/vvp		?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. 30483	\N	1895	2510	NATS - The Cloud Native Messaging System	NATS is an open-source, high-performance, lightweight and secure cloud native messaging system. NATS is a hosted CNCF project.	https://nats.io	https://github.com/nats-io	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	https://nats.io\r\nhttps://github.com/nats-io	Met	https://nats.io/about/	Met	https://nats.io/documentation/contributing/	Met	https://nats.io/documentation/contributing/\r\nDescribes filing bugs, issues, and pull requests for our GitHub repository 	Met	https://nats.io/documentation/contributing/\r\nCode Review Criteria\r\nKnowing whats likely to be accepted or rejected and why is a key consideration in deciding whether and what to contribute. The criteria below are things we think about and look for in any proposed change. We have Performance, Stability, Simplicity, and Security in mind at all times.\r\n\r\nSimply put, changes that have many or large positives, and few negative effects or risks, are much more likely to be merged, and merged quickly. Risky and less valuable changes are very unlikely to be merged, and may be rejected outright rather than receive iterations of review.\r\n\r\nPluses\r\n\r\nFixes the root cause of a bug in existing functionality\r\nAdds functionality or fixes a problem needed by a large number of users\r\nSimple, targeted\r\nMaintains or improves consistency across supported API languages\r\nEasily tested; has tests\r\nReduces complexity and lines of code\r\nChange has already been discussed and is known to the committers\r\n\r\nMinuses\r\n\r\nNon-optional new functionality that negatively affects performance\r\nBand-aids a symptom of a bug only\r\nIntroduces complex new functionality, especially an API that needs to be supported\r\nAdds complexity that only helps a niche use case\r\nAdds user-space functionality that does not need to be maintained as part of NATS\r\nChanges a public API or semantics (rarely allowed)\r\nAdds large dependencies\r\nChanges versions of existing dependencies\r\nAdds a large amount of code\r\nIs not modular/targeted  makes lots of modifications in one big bang change\r\nBreaks existing tests (implying your change is not backwards compatible)\r\nCode coverage decreases (implying you didnt add sufficient tests for new/changed code)	Met	https://github.com/nats-io/gnatsd/blob/master/LICENSE	Met	https://github.com/nats-io/gnatsd/blob/master/LICENSE The Apache-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI). Met	The main repository contains all versions of GLPI, whether in BETA, RELEASE-CANDIDATE, STABLE, we manage this in branches "BUGFIXES" (current STABLE version) and "MASTER" (future MAJOR version) : http://glpi-developer-documentation.readthedocs.io/en/master/sourcecode.html#branches	Met	Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.	Met	GLPI follows a semantic versioning scheme, on 3 digits. The first one is the major release, the second the minor and the third the fix release.\r\n\r\nMajor releases may come with important incompatibilities as well as new features; minor versions may bring new features as well, but stay perfectly compatible inside a major version.\r\n\r\nFixes releases will only fix reported issues without adding anything new. GLPI stands for **Gestionnaire Libre de Parc Informatique** is a Free Asset and IT Management Software package, that provides ITIL Service Desk features, licenses tracking and software auditing.\r\n\r\nGLPI features:\r\n* Inventory of computers, peripherals, network printers and any associated components through an interface, with inventory tools such as: [FusionInventory](http://fusioninventory.org/) or [OCS Inventory](https://www.ocsinventory-ng.org/fr/)\r\n* Data Center Infrastructure Management (DCIM)\r\n* Item lifecycle management\r\n* Licenses management (ITIL compliant)\r\n* Management of warranty and financial information (purchase order, warranty and extension, damping)\r\n* Management of contracts, contacts, documents related to inventory items\r\n* Incidents, requests, problems and changes management\r\n* Knowledge base and Frequently-Asked Questions (FAQ)\r\n* Asset reservation\r\n\r\nMoreover, GLPI supports many [plugins](http://plugins.glpi-project.org) that provide additional features.	2018-07-31T06:48:51.955Z	2019-01-04T09:01:51.258Z	Met		Met	ATM, GLPI uses CircleCI <https://github.com/glpi-project/glpi/blob/master/.circleci/config.yml> and TravisCI <https://github.com/glpi-project/glpi/blob/master/.travis.yml> for each commit (on pull-request or not).	cpe:2.3:a:glpi-project:glpi	Met	GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests. 30701	\N	2135	2821	drake	The drake R package is a general-purpose workflow manager for data-driven tasks in R. drake rebuilds intermediate data objects when their dependencies change, and it skips work when the results are already up to date. Not every runthrough starts from scratch, and completed workflows have tangible evidence of reproducibility.	https://ropensci.github.io/drake	https://github.com/ropensci/drake	GPL-3.0-only	?	\N	Met	https://ropenscilabs.github.io/drake-manual, https://ropensci.github.io/drake	Met	The main page at https://ropensci.github.io/drake provides motivating context and a user-friendly high-level overview.	Met	Installation instructions are at https://ropensci.github.io/drake/#installation, help and troubleshooting tips are at https://ropensci.github.io/drake/#help-and-troubleshooting, and https://ropensci.github.io/drake/#contributing and its subsections overview how to contribute.	Met	https://ropensci.github.io/drake/#contributing, https://github.com/ropensci/drake/blob/master/CONDUCT.md, https://github.com/ropensci/drake/blob/master/.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE.md, and https://github.com/ropensci/drake/blob/master/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md guide users through the contribution process.	Met	The pull request template at https://github.com/ropensci/drake/blob/master/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md has a checklist for incoming contributions.	Met	The DESCRIPTION file is the standard way to specify the license of an R package like drake. https://github.com/ropensci/drake/blob/ae914dae96c12b0030850388738bead900f83d89/DESCRIPTION#L14 declares a GPL-3 license. A GPL license for an R package does not need an explicit license file.	Met	GPL-3 attribution: https://github.com/ropensci/drake/blob/ae914dae96c12b0030850388738bead900f83d89/DESCRIPTION#L14 The GPL-3.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).	Met	The GPL-3.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).	Met	There is an extensive manual at https://ropenscilabs.github.io/drake-manual (development page: https://github.com/ropenscilabs/drake-manual) along with a plethora of resources linked from https://ropensci.github.io/drake/#documentation and its subsections.	Met	The extensive manual at  extensive manual at https://ropenscilabs.github.io/drake-manual go into detail about the interface, and help files at https://github.com/ropensci/drake/tree/master/man document and demonstrate every user-side function in full detail. The "man" folder is the standard way to document user-side functions and data objects in an R package.	Met	Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.	Met	Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made. Met	The drake package follows the versioning guide at http://r-pkgs.had.co.nz/release.html#release-version, the community accepted variant of semantic versioning for R packages. The technologies include REST APIs to enable CI/CD and system administration, a command-line interface that runs on the desktop (Mac, Linux, Windows) and a Desktop View that renders the mainframe in a familiar Desktop motif.\r\n\r\nIn addition to the core technologies, the project includes a variety of applications like TN3270, Z explorers for accessing files, submitting and retrieving job output as well as a communication framework to enable inter application communication.	https://zowe.org	https://github.com/zowe/zlc	EPL-2.0	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs.	Met	Zowe offers modern interfaces to interact with z/OS and allows you to work with z/OS in a way that is similar to what you experience on cloud platforms today. You can use these interfaces as delivered or through plug-ins and extensions that are created by clients or third-party vendors.\r\n\r\nZowe consists of the following main components.\r\n\r\nzLUX: Contains a Web user interface (UI) that provides a full screen interactive experience. The Web UI includes many interactions that exist in 3270 terminals and web interfaces such as IBM z/OSMF.\r\n\r\nExplorer server: Provides a range of APIs for the management of jobs, data sets, z/OS UNIX System Services files, and persistent data.\r\n\r\nAPI Mediation Layer: Provides an API abstraction layer through which APIs can be discovered, catalogued, and presented uniformly.\r\n\r\nZowe CLI: Provides a command-line interface that lets you interact with the mainframe remotely and use common tools such as Integrated Development Environments (IDEs), shell commands, bash scripts, and build tools for mainframe development. It provides a set of utilities and services for application developers that want to become efficient in supporting and building z/OS applications quickly.https://zowe.org\r\n\r\n	Met	https://zowe.org/contribute/	Met	https://zowe.org/code-guidelines-4/	Met	https://zowe.org/code-guidelines-4/	Met	https://github.com/zowe/imperative/blob/master/LICENSE\r\nhttps://github.com/zowe/zlux-platform/blob/master/LICENSE	Met	All software in the Zowe organization is licensed under the Eclipse Public License 2.0\r\n	Unmet	https://zowe.org/contribute/	Met	https://zowe.github.io/docs-site/	Met	https://zowe.github.io/docs-site/	Met	https://github.com/zowe	Met	Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made. 30821	\N	2268	2997	PostgreSQL	PostgreSQL is a powerful, open source object-relational database system that uses and extends the SQL language combined with many features that safely store and scale the most complicated data workloads. The origins of PostgreSQL date back to 1986 as part of the POSTGRES project at the University of California at Berkeley and has more than 30 years of active development on the core platform.\r\n\r\nPostgreSQL has earned a strong reputation for its proven architecture, reliability, data integrity, robust feature set, extensibility, and the dedication of the open source community behind the software to consistently deliver performant and innovative solutions. PostgreSQL runs on all major operating systems, has been ACID-compliant since 2001, and has powerful add-ons such as the popular PostGIS geospatial database extender. It is no surprise that PostgreSQL has become the open source relational database of choice for many people and organisations.\r\n\r\nGetting started with using PostgreSQL has never been easier - pick a project you want to build, and let PostgreSQL safely and robustly store your data.\r\n\r\nhttps://www.postgresql.org/about/	https://www.postgresql.org	https://git.postgresql.org/git/postgresql.git	PostgreSQL Licence	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. 30850	\N	2303	3064	ONAP AAF (Application Authorization Framework)	AAF is designed to cover Fine-Grained Authorization, meaning that the Authorizations provided are able to used an Applications detailed authorizations, such as whether a user may be on a particular page or has access to a particular Pub-SUB topic controlled within the App.\r\n\r\nAAF's Client Framework, "CADI" provide multi-Authentication to a normalized identity, which is paired with Authorization to provide full validation of incoming transaction before processing.\r\n\r\nThese are critical functions for Cloud environments, as Services need to be able to be installed and running in a very short time, and should not be encumbered with local stores of User Password and/or Permissions.	https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Application+Authorization+Framework+Project	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/aaf/authz	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. Met	https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aaf/authz.git/docs/index.html	Met		Met	https://gerrit.onap.org/r/aaf/authz	Met	Tracking is provided by using a combination of JIRA and git history. 30860	\N	2316	2279	Sidecar Reverse Proxy	The Sidecar Reverse Proxy service is a proxy microservice which intercepts incoming REST requests by, extracting the credentials from the request and authenticates/authorises with a configured security provider. The layer offers enterprise, cloud-like features such as high-availability, scalability, dynamic API discovery, consistent security, a single sign-on experience, and documentation. The API Mediation Layer facilitates secure communication across loosely coupled microservices through the API Gateway. 30876	\N	2332	3071	tpm2-tss	Open Source Software implementation of the TCG TPM2 Software Stack (TSS2).\r\nThe TSS2 project aims to facilitate the use of the Trusted Platform Module by providing various abstraction layers - from top to bottom:\r\n\r\n* Enhanced System API (ESAPI) as described in the [TSS 2.0 Enhanced System API (ESAPI) Specification](https://trustedcomputinggroup.org/wp-content/uploads/TSS_ESAPI_Version-0.9_Revision-04_reviewEND030918.pdf).\r\nThis API is a 1-to-1 mapping of the TPM2 commands documented in Part 3 of the TPM2 specification.\r\nAdditionally there are asynchronous versions of each command.\r\nIn addition to SAPI, the ESAPI performs tracking of meta data for TPM object and automatic calculation of session based authorization and encryption values.\r\nBoth the synchronous and asynchronous API are exposed through a single library: libtss2-esys.\r\n* System API (SAPI) as described in the [system level API and TPM command transmission interface specification](http://www.trustedcomputinggroup.org/resources/tss_system_level_api_and_tpm_command_transmission_interface_specification).\r\nThis API is a 1-to-1 mapping of the TPM2 commands documented in Part 3 of the TPM2 specification.\r\nAdditionally there are asynchronous versions of each command.\r\nThese asynchronous variants may be useful for integration into event-driven programming environments.\r\nBoth the synchronous and asynchronous API are exposed through a single library: libtss2-sys.\r\n* Marshaling/Unmarshaling (MU) as described in the [TCG TSS 2.0 Marshaling/Unmarshaling API Specification](https://trustedcomputinggroup.org/wp-content/uploads/TSS_Marshaling_Unmarshaling_API_Version-1.0_Revision-04_review_ENDS030918.pdf).\r\nThis API provides a set of marshaling and unmarshaling functions for all data types define by the TPM library specification.\r\nThe Marshaling/Unmarshaling API is exposed through a library called libtss2-mu.\r\n* TPM Command Transmission Interface (TCTI) that is described in the same specification.\r\nThis API provides a standard interface to transmit / receive TPM command / response buffers.\r\nIt is expected that any number of libraries implementing the TCTI API will be implemented as a way to abstract various platform specific IPC mechanisms.\r\nCurrently this repository provides two TCTI implementations: libtss2-tcti-device and libtss2-tcti-mssim.\r\nThe former should be used for direct access to the TPM through the Linux kernel driver.\r\nThe latter implements the protocol exposed by the Microsoft software TPM2 simulator.\r\n* The [TCG TSS 2.0 Overview and Common Structures Specification](https://trustedcomputinggroup.org/wp-content/uploads/TSS_Overview_Common_Structures_Version-0.9_Revision-03_Review_030918.pdf) forms the basis for all implementations in this project. NOTE: We deviate from this draft of the specification by increasing the value of TPM2_NUM_PCR_BANKS from 3 to 16 to ensure compatibility with TPM2 implementations that have enabled a larger than typical number of PCR banks. This larger value for TPM2_NUM_PCR_BANKS is expected to be included in a future revision of the specification.	https://github.com/tpm2-software/tpm2-tss	https://github.com/tpm2-software/tpm2-tss	BSD-2-Clause	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs - feature by Github	Met	https://github.com/tpm2-software/tpm2-tss/blob/master/README.md	Met	<https://github.com/tpm2-software/tpm2-tss/blob/master/README.md> and <https://github.com/tpm2-software/tpm2-tss/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md>\r\n	Met	Non-trivial contribution file in repository: <https://github.com/tpm2-software/tpm2-tss/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md>. 30924	\N	2381	3172	Hyperledger Caliper	Caliper is a blockchain benchmark framework which allows users to measure the performance of a specific blockchain implementation with a set of predefined use cases. Caliper will produce reports containing a number of performance indicators, such as TPS (Transactions Per Second), transaction latency, resource utilisation etc. The intent is for Caliper results to be used as a reference in supporting the choice of a blockchain implementation suitable for the user-specific use-cases. The project uses AES256 GCM to encrypt the session cookie after successful OpenID Connect and protects from CSRF https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_(CSRF)_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet#Encrypted_Token_Pattern with an encrypted query to validate the redirect request is coming from us.\r\n\r\nThe project uses `crypto/md5` only in tests to generate test content. 31094	\N	2570	3406	system-support-specialist	System support specialists provide help desk assistance and technical support for all types of issues affecting end users, such as software problems, network breakdowns, and hardware failures. 31105	\N	2582	3460	LinuxTV	 The LinuxTV community develops and maintains the Linux Kernel Media Subsystems and several userspace libraries and applications.\r\n\r\nThe Linux Kernel Media Subsystems provide support for devices like webcams, streaming capture and output, analog TV, digital TV, AM/FM radio, Sofware Digital Radio (SDR), remote controllers and encoders/decoders for compressed video formats. It offers native support for a large number of drivers for commonly available PCI cards and USB devices, but the subsystems are also targeted towards Linux based set-top-boxes and embedded devices like mobile phones. \r\n\r\nThe main goal is to develop the Linux Kernel media subsystem.\r\n\r\nWe also develop a series of userspace applications, tools and libraries: v4l-utils, ZBar, Kaffeine, XawTv, TVtime, Camorama, EDID decode, Digital TV tables. While several applications are used primarely by end users, for the developers of the project, their primary goal is to be able to test the Kernel development and to provide userspace libraries to enhance the media subsystem support. 	https://linuxtv.org	https://git.linuxtv.org	GPL-2.0-only	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. 31259	\N	2786	3761	Predator: an open source performance testing platform for APIs	Predator is a performance testing platform for APIs. It manages the entire lifecycle of load testing APIs, from creating and managing existing performance tests, to running these tests on a scheduled and on-demand basis, and finally viewing the test results in a highly informative and live built-in report.\r\n\r\nPredator has a simple, one-click installation, built with support for Kubernetes (helm charts), DC/OS (mesosphere universe), and Docker Engine, and can persist the created performance tests and their reports in 5 different databases. It also supports running distributed load out of the box, enabling an unlimited amount of virtual users that can bombard your servers. Bootstrapped with a user-friendly UI alongside a simple REST API, Predator helps developers simplify the performance testing regime.\r\n\r\nhttps://zooz.github.io/predator/images/predator-screens.gif	https://predator-ng.com	https://github.com/Zooz/predator	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs. 31422	\N	2964	3983	mockolo	Mockolo is a mock generator for Swift. Swift doesn't provide mocking support, and Mockolo provides a fast and easy way to autogenerate mock objects that can be tested in your code. One of the main objectives of Mockolo is performance. Unlike other frameworks, Mockolo provides highly performant and scalable generation of mocks via a lightweight commandline tool, so it can run as part of a linter or during a build if one chose to do so. Try Mockolo and enhance your project's test coverage in an efficient, performant way.	https://github.com/uber/mockolo	https://github.com/uber/mockolo	Apache-2.0	?	\N	Met	https://github.com/uber/mockolo	Met	Mockolo is a mock generator for Swift. Swift doesn't provide mocking support, and Mockolo provides a fast and easy way to autogenerate mock objects that can be tested in your code. One of the main objectives of Mockolo is performance. Unlike other frameworks, Mockolo provides highly performant and scalable generation of mocks via a lightweight commandline tool, so it can run as part of a linter or during a build if one chose to do so. Try Mockolo and enhance your project's test coverage in an efficient, performant way.\r\n\r\n	Met	https://github.com/uber/mockolo/blob/master/README.md#report-any-issues shows how to file an issue or provide feedback.  https://github.com/uber/mockolo/blob/master/README.md#how-to-contribute-to-mockolo shows how to contribute to the project. N/A	the bittorrent protocol does not use any cryptographic primitives. There is however support for encrypted bittorrent swarms in libtorrent, as an extension. But it cannot be on by default. Met	The only keys used in bittorrent are for SSL, which supports everything openSSL does. the ed25519 keys used in the DHT mutable puts are 32 bytes (256 bits)	Met	All crypto is done by openssl (some obfuscation is done using RC4, but is not advertised as providing any confidentiality)	Met	the only confidential channels are implemented by OpenSSL.	N/A	there is no storing of passwords or keys. 31588	\N	3172	4267	Medical Imaging Diagnosis Assistant	The goal of this project is to propose a new methodology for fully automated breast cancer detection and segmentation from multi-modal medical images introducing clinical covariates. This protocol provides the following novelties. First, it lies on the use of deep convolutional neural networks (CNNs) that will incorporate several image modalities: 3D magnetic resonance images (MRI), ultrasound (US) or Mammography (MG) views. This is the first methodology that is able to classify a whole exam, containing all the above image modalities.\r\n\r\nIn this project, we are interested to develop a new assistant (i.e. a system that will provide diagnosis support as a second opinion), for other human tissues, besides the breast. This will embrace other anatomies such as the aorta, spinal column, epicardial fat, body fat, heart, lungs, and muscle.	https://github.com/mida-project	https://github.com/mida-project/meta	GPL-3.0	?	\N	Met	Given only https: URLs.
